  "prompt": "How is a chemical equation formed?",
  "response": "A chemical equation is formed through several key steps:\n\n1. Reactants and Products\n- Reactants are substances that enter the reaction\n- Products are substances formed by the reaction\n- Separated by an arrow (\u2192) pointing from reactants to products\n\n2. Chemical Symbols\n- Use chemical symbols and formulas of elements and compounds\n- Represent the specific atoms and molecules involved\n\n3. Balancing the Equation\n- Ensure the number of atoms of each element is the same on both sides\n- Add coefficients in front of compounds to equalize atom numbers\n- Maintains the law of conservation of mass\n\n4. Example\nUnbalanced: H2 + O2 \u2192 H2O\nBalanced: 2H2 + O2 \u2192 2H2O\n\n5. Additional Notation\n- Optional state symbols (s, l, g, aq) can be added\n- Optional reaction conditions like heat or catalyst can be included\n\n6. Types of Equations\n- Synthesis (combination)\n- Decomposition\n- Single displacement\n- Double displacement\n- Combustion\n\nThe goal is to accurately represent the chemical transformation while maintaining the fundamental principles of chemical reactions.",
